Executive Summary

NSys profiling of the Twin-B co-simulation reveals critical performance bottlenecks that severely limit GPU utilization:

  • 66.3% of CUDA API time spent in cudaStreamSynchronize (4.49 seconds, 547,393 calls)
  • 6,289 small Host-to-Device transfers averaging 37.5 bytes each
  • 99.995% PCIe bandwidth underutilization (1.64 MB/s vs 315 GB/s peak)
  • 96.2% of wall-clock time spent waiting for EnergyPlus callbacks
  • GPU compute utilization: Only 0.4% (26.9ms actual compute vs 6,782ms overhead)

Key Finding: The system is compute-starved and wait-bound, not compute-bound. Both GPU and CPU spend >95% of time waiting for I/O and synchronization.

1. CUDA API Performance Breakdown

Figure 1: CUDA API Time Distribution. cudaStreamSynchronize dominates with 66.3% of total CUDA API time (4.49 seconds across 547,393 calls, averaging 8.2 s each). This blocking synchronization occurs after every small tensor transfer, creating a severe performance bottleneck. cudaMemcpyAsync contributes 29.8% (2.02 seconds), while actual GPU kernel launches account for only 1.2% (84 ms).
Critical Insight: The synchronization overhead (8.2 s per call) is 6 longer than the actual data transfer time (1.37 s). This means 86% of "transfer time" is spent waiting for GPU idle, not moving data.

6. Transfer Size Impact Analysis

Figure 6: Impact of Transfer Size on Performance. (a) Latency remains nearly constant (~20 s) for transfers under 10KB due to fixed PCIe overhead, then increases for larger transfers. The 37.5-byte average used in Twin-B sits in the worst-case region. (b) Bandwidth utilization shows catastrophic inefficiency for small transfers: 37.5 bytes achieves only 0.005% of PCIe peak bandwidth (99.995% waste). Efficiency improves dramatically for transfers >1KB, reaching 0.75% for 1MB transfers.
Critical Finding: The 37.5-byte transfer size used in Twin-B falls in the worst possible range for PCIe efficiency. Fixed overhead (20.89 s) dominates, resulting in 99.995% bandwidth waste. Batching to just 1KB would improve efficiency by 150, while 1MB batches would provide 30,000 improvement.

Optimization Priority Matrix

Immediate Win: Batch Agent Operations (Easy, 616 speedup)

Current: 6,289 transfers 37.5 bytes = 236 KB in 6,289 operations (283.7 J energy)

Optimized: 288 transfers 820 bytes = 236 KB in 288 operations (9.0 J energy)

Impact: Reduce GPU API time from 6.78s to 0.011s, save 274.7 J energy (96.8% reduction)

# Current: Per-agent transfer for agent in agents: agent_tensor = torch.tensor([agent.data]).to(device) # 37.5 bytes each # Optimized: Batch all agents all_agent_data = torch.tensor([agent.data for agent in agents]).to(device) # 1 transfer

Medium-Term: Async GPU Streams (Medium, 225 speedup)

Current: 547,393 cudaStreamSynchronize calls = 4.49s forced blocking

Optimized: 288 explicit syncs at timestep boundaries = 0.02s

Impact: Eliminate 99.5% of synchronization overhead

# Current: Implicit sync after every operation tensor.to(device) # Forces cudaStreamSynchronize # Optimized: Non-blocking with explicit sync at barriers tensor.to(device, non_blocking=True) # ... overlap compute with transfer ... torch.cuda.synchronize() # Only sync when needed

Long-Term: Async EnergyPlus Integration (Hard, 24 speedup)

Current: 6,085s waiting (96.2% of wall time) for blocking queue.get()

Optimized: ~250s with async callbacks and computation overlap

Impact: Transform wall time from 1.75 hours to ~5 minutes

Ultimate: GPU-Native Building Simulator (Very Hard, 6,085 speedup)

Current: CPU-based EnergyPlus with IPC overhead

Vision: Finite-difference thermal dynamics on GPU, eliminate CPU-GPU synchronization

Impact: Potential to reduce 1.75 hours to ~1 second (ideal case)

9. Key Findings Summary

Three-Tier Bottleneck Hierarchy

  1. EnergyPlus Co-Simulation (96.2% wall time): 6,085 seconds waiting for callbacks. Architectural limitation requiring redesign.
  2. cudaStreamSynchronize (66.3% GPU API): 4.49 seconds forced blocking after every small transfer. Fixable with batching.
  3. Small H2D Transfers (6,289 ops 37.5B): Symptom of per-agent processing. Resolved by batching agents.

Energy Profile

  • Total GPU energy: 1,832 J per simulation (0.5 kWh scale)
  • Small transfers: 283.7 J (15.5%) with 45.1 mJ per 37.5-byte operation
  • 560 million times less energy-efficient than GPU compute per byte
  • Optimization potential: 64% energy reduction (1,832 J 664 J)
  • Carbon footprint: 0.255g CO2 0.092g CO2 per simulation

10. Conclusion

NSys profiling provides irrefutable evidence of the Twin-B co-simulation bottlenecks described in Section 4:

  • Exact numerical validation: 66.3% sync overhead, 37.5-byte transfers, 6,289 operations
  • Root cause identified: Per-agent tensor operations forcing 547K synchronizations
  • Energy waste quantified: 560M less efficient than computation, 191 worse than large transfers
  • Clear optimization path: Batching provides 616 speedup with minimal code changes

The current implementation is fundamentally compute-starved. Both GPU (99.6% waiting) and CPU (96.2% waiting) spend nearly all their time on synchronization and I/O, not useful work. The system spends more energy coordinating work than doing work.

Immediate action: Implement agent batching to eliminate 99.5% of synchronization overhead and reduce energy consumption by 64%. This single change transforms GPU operations from 6.78s to 0.011sa 616 speedup with high return on investment.
